    <fr:title text="join of \infty -categories is a \infty -category">join of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>-categories is a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>-category</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Given two <fr:link href="/forest/htt-0001/" title="\infty -category" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/htt-0001/" display-uri="htt-0001" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>-categories</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X, Y]]></fr:tex>, their <fr:link href="/forest/htt-000B/" title="join of (augmented) simplicial set" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/htt-000B/" display-uri="htt-000B" type="local">join</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \star  Y]]></fr:tex> is still an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>-category.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>3</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    The vertices of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \star  Y]]></fr:tex> is given by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_0 \sqcup  Y_0]]></fr:tex>. Consider a horn <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Lambda ^n_i]]></fr:tex>. Suppose its vertices lie entirely within <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_0]]></fr:tex>, then all its higher simplices are in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> too, so we can fill the horn within <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Similarly for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    For the other cases, notice that an edge can only go from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> and not backwards. As long as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(n, i) \ne  (2, 0), (2, 2)]]></fr:tex> — which does not occur since we only need inner horns — we know the first <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> vertices are in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and the rest are in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and we can restrict the horn along <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ^{ \{0, \dots , k-1\} } \hookrightarrow  \Lambda ^n_i]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ^{ \{k, \dots , n\} } \hookrightarrow  \Lambda ^n_i]]></fr:tex>. From this we can construct the simplex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ^n \to  X \star  Y]]></fr:tex> by definition of the join.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
